However, it is worth considering a mixed strategy approach, where I occasionally switch between R and B to exploit the potential for higher payouts when my opponent chooses differently. In this case, I might choose to deviate from B approximately every 25 rounds (one out of every three deviations would be R and two out of every three would be B). This strategy would still provide an average payout of around 14.74$ per round over the course of 75 rounds, with a higher potential for earning more in some rounds due to the 40$ payout when I choose R while my opponent chooses B.

Ultimately, the choice between a consistent B strategy and a mixed strategy would depend on factors such as the specific rules of the experiment, whether deviations from the chosen strategy are observed or not, and my tolerance for risk. In this case, I will choose B consistently, appending the choice letter as follows: {B}
